🔹 1. Advanced Database Operations
 a) Indexing (Very Important)

Indexes improve query speed by avoiding full table scans.

Types of Indexes:
Single-column index
Composite index (multiple columns)
Unique index
Full-text index
Example:
CREATE INDEX idx_user_email ON users(email);

 b) Joins Optimization

Efficient joins reduce execution time.

Types:
INNER JOIN
LEFT JOIN
RIGHT JOIN
FULL JOIN
Tips:
Join on indexed columns
Avoid unnecessary joins
Use proper join order
 c) Transactions

Ensure data consistency (ACID properties)

Atomicity
Consistency
Isolation
Durability
Example:
BEGIN;
UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance - 100 WHERE id = 1;
UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance + 100 WHERE id = 2;
COMMIT;
 d) Stored Procedures

Reusable SQL logic inside DB

CREATE PROCEDURE GetUsers()
BEGIN
  SELECT * FROM users;
END;
 e) Views

Virtual tables based on queries

CREATE VIEW active_users AS
SELECT * FROM users WHERE status = 'active';
 f) Partitioning

Split large tables into smaller parts

Types:
Range partitioning
Hash partitioning
List partitioning

🔹 2. Query Optimization Techniques
⚡ a) Use EXPLAIN

Analyze query execution plan

EXPLAIN SELECT * FROM orders WHERE user_id = 10;


Index usage
Scan type
Cost
⚡ b) Avoid SELECT *

Bad:

SELECT * FROM users;

Good:

SELECT name, email FROM users;
⚡ c) Use WHERE Clauses Efficiently
Filter early
Use indexed columns
⚡ d) Limit Data
SELECT * FROM users LIMIT 10;
⚡ e) Avoid N+1 Queries

Bad (multiple queries):

SELECT * FROM users;
SELECT * FROM orders WHERE user_id = 1;

🔹 3. Database Optimization Techniques
a) Normalization vs Denormalization
Normalization
Removes redundancy
Improves consistency
Denormalization
Improves read performance
Adds redundancy
  b) Caching

Store frequently accessed data

Tools:
Redis
Memcached
 c) Connection Pooling

Reuse DB connections instead of creating new ones

Improves performance under heavy load

 d) Replication
Master → Slave replication
Read from replicas

 Improves scalability

e) Sharding

Split database across multiple servers

👉 Used for very large systems (e.g., social media apps)

